## 3.0 The Anaerobic System

### 3.1 What It Is

The anaerobic systems produce ATP without oxygen, via two pathways: the **phosphocreatine (PCr) system** (near-instant, lasts ~6–10 seconds, used for sprinting/starts) and **anaerobic glycolysis** (rapid, lasts roughly 30 seconds to 2–3 minutes, the dominant contributor to efforts like an all-out 400–800m). Both produce **lactate and hydrogen ions** as by-products, which is the actual physiological cause of the "burning" sensation and the loss of force production in hard, short efforts.

### 3.2 Why It Matters

For a typical recreational or sub-elite road/distance runner, the anaerobic system's *direct* contribution to race performance is small for any event 5K and longer (commonly estimated at single-digit percentages of total energy contribution in a 5K, and negligible in a half marathon or marathon). However, it matters indirectly in three ways an AI engine should track:

1. **Finishing kicks and surges** in any race distance rely on anaerobic capacity even when the race itself is aerobically dominated.
2. **VO2 max training (Part 3)** deliberately recruits some anaerobic contribution as a side effect of running at very high intensities — this is expected and not a flaw in the workout.
3. **Neuromuscular power and stride mechanics** developed via short, fast anaerobic-system work (strides, hill sprints) carry over into running economy (Section 6) even for marathoners who will never race anaerobically.

### 3.3 How Training Changes It

Anaerobic capacity and power respond quickly (within 2–4 weeks) to short, maximal-effort training, but this is also the *most injury-risky and most easily overdone* training stimulus in the entire system, because of the high forces and high neuromuscular demand involved. This is why this knowledge base treats true anaerobic-system work (sprinting, all-out 200–400m repeats) as a small, carefully dosed supplement — never a primary training focus — for any runner targeting 5K or longer.

**AI Rule 3.1 — Anaerobic Work Dosing**
```
FOR goal_event ≥ 5K:
   anaerobic_specific_work (sprints, all-out short reps) should never
   exceed a small minority of total weekly high-intensity volume,
   and should be introduced only after an adequate aerobic base and
   threshold foundation exist (see Part 5, base phase prerequisites).

FOR goal_event ≤ 1500m:
   anaerobic contribution is performance-relevant and should be
   trained directly and progressively — see Part 6 for event-specific
   handling (out of scope for most adult-recreational-app users but
   retained for completeness).
```

