## 4.0 Lactate Threshold

### 4.1 What It Is — and the Two-Threshold Model

"Lactate threshold" is colloquially used as a single term but is more accurately understood as **two distinct physiological landmarks**, and the AI engine should treat them as separate variables, not one:

- **LT1 (aerobic threshold)** — roughly the highest intensity at which blood lactate remains only slightly above resting levels (commonly referenced near ~2 mmol/L, though absolute values vary by individual and by assay). Below this point, effort is almost purely aerobic and can be sustained for very long durations with minimal accumulating fatigue.
- **LT2 (lactate threshold / maximal lactate steady state, MLSS)** — the highest intensity at which the body can still *clear* lactate as fast as it's produced, so blood lactate stabilises rather than rising continuously (commonly referenced near ~4 mmol/L, again individually variable). Above LT2, lactate (and fatigue) accumulates progressively and the pace cannot be held indefinitely. A review of lactate-threshold concepts noted that LT1 and LT2 are genuinely distinct physiological landmarks, and that training at LT1 produces dramatically less metabolic and neuromuscular fatigue cost than training at or above LT2.

### 4.2 Why It Matters More Than VO2 Max for Most Race Distances

For half marathon and marathon racing especially, **LT2 (and the runner's ability to sustain a pace just below it) is a stronger predictor of performance than VO2 max alone**, because these races are run at intensities close to threshold, not close to maximal aerobic capacity. This is precisely why the modern Norwegian system (Part 10) is built around *lactate-controlled threshold volume* rather than maximal-effort interval volume — the philosophy is to accumulate as much high-quality time as possible just below LT2, because that is the literal physiological zone the races are contested in, while staying below the point where fatigue cost becomes prohibitively high.

### 4.3 How Training Changes It

Threshold training raises LT2 primarily by improving the muscle's capacity to *clear and buffer* lactate and hydrogen ions (via mitochondrial adaptations, monocarboxylate transporter density, and buffering capacity), allowing the same absolute pace to be sustained at a lower relative physiological cost — which is also why an improving runner's **lactate curve shifts right** (the same blood lactate concentration now occurs at a faster pace) even when VO2 max itself barely changes. This is one of the most trainable variables in distance running and typically the single highest-leverage system to develop for 10K-through-marathon athletes.

**AI Rule 4.1 — Threshold as the Primary Lever for 10K–Marathon Athletes**
```
IF goal_event ∈ {10K, Half Marathon, Marathon}
   AND athlete has an adequate aerobic base (Section 2)
THEN threshold-zone work (Part 3, "Threshold" zone) should receive
     the largest share of total weekly high-intensity volume,
     ahead of VO2 max work — this is a deliberate, evidence-aligned
     prioritisation, not an oversight.
```

