## 7.0 Fat Oxidation

### 7.1 What It Is

Fat oxidation is the use of stored fat (triglycerides, both intramuscular and from adipose tissue) as fuel for aerobic metabolism. Fat is an almost limitlessly abundant fuel source even in lean athletes, but it can only be metabolised aerobically and at a comparatively slow rate, which is why the body must blend it with carbohydrate, with the *ratio* shifting toward more carbohydrate use as intensity rises.

### 7.2 Why It Matters

The point at which fat oxidation rate peaks (sometimes called "FatMax") typically sits in a moderate-intensity aerobic zone — broadly in the same territory as the easy/Zone 2 training intensity covered in Part 3, which is part of the physiological justification for that zone's popular framing as "fat-burning." For distance events from the marathon upward, maximising fat oxidation capacity is directly performance-relevant: it spares limited glycogen stores (Section 8), delaying the point of glycogen depletion that causes catastrophic late-race slowdown (colloquially "the wall").

### 7.3 How Training Changes It

Fat oxidation capacity improves with **chronic low-to-moderate intensity volume** — again pointing back to the aerobic base (Section 2) as the primary driver — and can be further sharpened with deliberately glycogen-depleted easy/long running (e.g., a portion of long runs done in a partially fueled or fasted state, sometimes used by marathon-focused athletes), though this comes with trade-offs (reduced session quality, increased perceived effort, and — for athletes with any disordered-eating risk factors — a practice the AI engine should never recommend without real caution, deferring to Part 1's wellbeing-first constraints).

**AI Rule 7.1 — Fat Oxidation Relevance Gate**
```
IF goal_event ∈ {Half Marathon, Marathon}
THEN fat-oxidation development is directly performance-relevant;
     prioritise consistent easy-pace long runs as the primary lever.

IF athlete shows any indicator of disordered eating risk or
   excessive focus on body composition (see Part 1 wellbeing constraints)
THEN do not suggest fasted training or deliberate glycogen depletion
     under any circumstances, regardless of event distance.
```

