## 8.0 Glycogen Utilisation

### 8.1 What It Is

Glycogen is the body's stored form of carbohydrate (in muscle and liver), and it is the preferred and most efficient fuel at moderate-to-high running intensities. Total glycogen stores are finite — commonly estimated at roughly 90–120 minutes of continuous moderate-to-hard running for a well-fueled but untrained store, extendable through training adaptations and in-race fueling.

### 8.2 Why It Matters

Glycogen depletion is the proximate physiological cause of the marathon "wall": as muscle glycogen runs low, the body is forced to rely more heavily on the slower fat-oxidation pathway (Section 7) at a pace that demands faster ATP turnover than fat alone can supply, forcing a involuntary pace collapse. This is why marathon-specific training (Part 6) places such heavy emphasis on (a) long runs that push glycogen-depletion adaptations, (b) practising in-race carbohydrate fueling, and (c) building the aerobic/fat-oxidation base that delays depletion in the first place.

### 8.3 How Training Changes It

Training increases **glycogen storage capacity** (trained muscle can store meaningfully more glycogen than untrained muscle) and improves the *efficiency* of glycogen use at a given pace (a direct overlap with running economy, Section 6). Long runs and glycogen-depleting sessions also train the gut to tolerate in-race carbohydrate intake — an underrated, highly practical adaptation that has nothing to do with cardiovascular fitness but is frequently the actual limiter in marathon performance.

**AI Rule 8.1 — Fueling Rehearsal Requirement (Marathon/Half Marathon)**
```
FOR goal_event ∈ {Half Marathon, Marathon}:
   AT LEAST the final 3–4 long runs before the race must include
   in-race-identical carbohydrate fueling practice (type, timing,
   quantity) — this is treated as a mandatory specificity requirement
   (Part 1, Section 6), not an optional add-on.
```

